{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Which I hoard for the time of distress,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
for the day of assault and of battle?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Which way are the vapours divided,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
That scatter on earth the cool water?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}Who cleft for the torrents a channel,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
A path for the flash of the lightning\uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Sending rain on the desolate land,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
On the uninhabited desert,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}Thus gladdening the wilderness waste,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And the thirsty land clothing with verdure?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}Say, hath the rain a father?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or who hath begotten the dew-drops?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}Out of whose womb issued the ice?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And the hoar-frost of heaven \uc1\u8211* who hath borne it?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}The waters are frozen like stone,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And the face of the deep remains hidden.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}Dost thou fasten the chain of the dog-star
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or loosen the bonds or Orion?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}Dost thou bring out the stars in their season?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
The Bear with her young dost thou lead?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}Dost thou lay down the law to the heavens,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or establish their rule in the earth?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}Dost thou lift up thy voice to the clouds,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
That abundance of waters obey thee?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 35}Dost thou send on their mission the lightnings?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
To thee do they say, "Here we are"?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 36}Who hath set in the fleecy clouds wisdom?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or given to the meteor insight?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 37}Who spreadeth the clouds out in wisdom?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Who tilteth the pitchers of heaven,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 38}When the dust runneth into a mass
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And the clods cleave firmly together?
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Wonders of the Animate World

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 39}Dost thou hunt for the lion his prey
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or the young lions\uc1\u8217* craving appease,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 40}When low in their lairs they crouch,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Lying in wait in the thicket?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 41}Who provideth at even his food,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
When his young ones cry unto God,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Open-mouthed, for the meat that is lacking?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\cf1\f1\fs22 39}Dost thou fix the birth-times of the wild goats,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or watch o\uc1\u8217*er the calving of hinds?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Dost thou number the months they fulfil,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or determine the time of their bearing?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}They cower and bring forth their young,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Swiftly ridding themselves of their birth-pangs.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Their young one grow strong in the open,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Go forth and come back not again.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Who let out the wild ass free?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Who loosened the bonds of the wild ass,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Whose home I have made the steppe,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And the salt-land the place of his dwelling?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}He laughs at the din of the city,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
No driver roars in his ears.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}The mountains he scours as his pasture,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And every green thing is his quest.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Will the wild ox be willing to serve thee,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or spend the night in thy crib?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Wilt thou fasten a rope on his neck?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Will he harrow thy furrows behind thee?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Wilt thou trust his magnificent strength,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or put him in charge of thy labours,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Expect him to come again
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And gather thy seed to thy threshing-floor?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}The wing of the ostrich beats joyously,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
But her pinions and feathers are cruel.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}For she trusteth her eggs to the ground,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And she setteth them down in the dust,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Forgetting that foot may crush them,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or beast of the field tread upon them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Her young she treats harshly, as strangers,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Unmoved though her toil be in vain.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}For God hath not dealt to her wisdom,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Nor alloted to her understanding.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}She scuddeth along in her flight,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
At the horse and his rider she laugheth.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}Dost thou give to the war-horse his strength,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Clothe his neck with the quivering mane?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Dost thou make him to leap like a locust,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
With snort that is splendid and terrible?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}He paweth the valley exulting,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
As forth to the fight the fares.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}He laughs undismayed at the terror,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
He turneth not back from the sword.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}Against him the quiver may rattle,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
The glittering spear or the dart:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}He devoureth the ground in wild rage,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Without turning to right hand or left.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}At the trumpet alarm he saith "Ha!"
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
For he scenteth the battle afar,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
The thunder of captains, the shouting.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}Doth the hawk soar aloft by thy wisdom.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And spread out her wings to the south?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}Doth the eagle mount up at thy bidding,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And make her nest high on the mountains?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}The cliff is her home where she lodges\uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
The peak of the cliff and the fortress,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}She spieth her prey from the heights
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
With those eyes that see from afar.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}Her young ones suck up blood:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Where the slain are, there is she.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs32 The Rebuke

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\cf1\f1\fs22 40}Shall a caviller strive with Almighty?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}He that argues with God \uc1\u8211* let him answer.
\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Then Job answered Jehovah and said:
\par}

{\pard
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Ah, how small am I! What can I answer?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
I lay my hand on my mouth.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Once indeed have I spoken; \uc1\u8211* enough:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Yea twice \uc1\u8211* but not ever again.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Wilt thou disallow my right.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And condemn me that thou mayest be justified?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}Hast thou an arm like God?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
With a voice like His canst thou thunder?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Now deck thee with pride and with majesty,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Clothe thee with glory and splendour.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Pour forth the floods of thine anger,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And all that is lofty abase.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Every proud one lay low whom thou seest,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And crush thou the wicked beneath thee.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Hide them together in dust,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And bind their faces in darkness.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}And I then will render thee praise
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
That thy right hand hath won thee the victory.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs44 Two Wonderful Creatures of God

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Hippopotamus

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Behold now the huge beast beside thee:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
He eateth up grass like an ox.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}Behold now the strength in his loins,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And the force in the muscles of his belly.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}He holds his tail stiff as a cedar,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
His thighs are of sinews entwined.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}His bones are as tubes of brass,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
His limbs are like bars of iron.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}He is chief of the ways of God,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Made to lord it over his fellows.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}The mountains yields him their fruits;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
All the wild beasts he grindeth to powder.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}There under the lotus he lies,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
In the covert of reed and fen,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}Protected by shade of the lotus,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Encircled by water-willows.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}From the wild rushing torrent he flees not;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
He is calm in the swell of a Jordan.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}Who would venture to make for his eyes,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or to pierce through his nose with a cord?
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Crocodile

\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\cf1\f1\fs22 41}Canst thou draw out the crocodile with hook,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or press his tongue down with a cord?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}Canst thou put a rope into his nose,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or pierce his jaws through with a hook?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3}Will he make many prayers unto thee,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or will he speak softly to thee?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 4}Will he make any tryst with thee,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
To be kept as thy servant for ever?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}Wilt thou play with him as with a bird,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or attach him to string for thy maidens?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}Shall the (fisher) guilds traffic in him?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Shall the merchants divide him in pieces?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}Canst thou fill his skin with barbs,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or his head with the fish-harpon?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}Lay but thine hand upon him:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Remember the battle \uc1\u8211* enough!
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}See! thy hope is but an illusion;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
God hurleth the dread of him far.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}Not one is so bold as to rouse him;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Where is he that can stand before him?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}Who hath ever triumphantly braved him?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Beneath the whole heaven, not one.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Of his limbs I will not keep silence,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Of his strength and his mighty equipment.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}Who can lay bare the face of his garment,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Or enter the folds of his breastplate?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}Who can open the doors of his face?
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Round about his teeth lieth terror.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}His back is a ripple of shields,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And his breast is a seal of flint.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}One shield is so near to another
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
That no air can come between them.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Each cleaveth so close to his fellow,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
So locked, that they cannot be served.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 18}Through the breath of his nostrils light flashes,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
His eyes are the lids of the morning.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 19}Out of his mouth go torches
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And sparks of fire leap forth.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 20}Smoke issues out of his nostrils,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Like a seething and boiling pot.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 21}His breath setteth coals ablaze,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And a flame goeth forth from his mouth.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 22}His neck is the home of strength,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And terror danceth before him.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 23}The flakes of his flesh are welded
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
So firm that they cannot be moved.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 24}His heart is as firm as a stone\uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Yea, firm as the nether mill-stone.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 25}When he lifts himself, strong men are terrified;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
At his teeth are the mighty dismayed.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 26}No sword availeth against him,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Nor spear nor dart nor arrow.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 27}He counteth iron as straw,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And brass as rotten wood;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 28}No arrow can put him to flight;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
On him sling-stones are turned to stubble.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 29}Clubs are counted as reed,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And he laughs at the whirr of a javelin.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 30}Beneath him (his scales, like) sharp sherds
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Spread marks, as of sledge, on the mire.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 31}He makes the deep boil like a pot;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
He stirreth the sea like ointment.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 32}In his wake is a shinning path\uc1\u8211*
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
One would think the deep to be hoary.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 33}There is not his like upon earth,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
Created to know no fear.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 34}Everything that is high is afraid of him:
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
He is king o\uc1\u8217*er the sons of pride.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\cf1\f1\fs22 42}I acknowledge that Thou hast prevailed;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 2}There is nothing too hard for Thee.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3b}Therefore spake I without understanding,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 3c}Of wonders beyond my knowledge.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 5}I had heard of Thee but by hearsay,
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
But now mine eye hath seen Thee;
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2440\li2800
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 6}And therefore I spurn (my words)
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi-2080\li2800
And repent in dust and in ashes.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs32 The Epilogue

\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Friends Rebuked

\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 7}So after Jehovah has spoken these words to Job,He said to Eliphaz the Temanite, "My anger ishot against thee and thy two friends; because,unlike my servant Job, ye have not spoken the{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 8}truth about me. But now, go to my servant Jobwith seven bullocks and seven rams, and offer themas a burnt-offering for yourselves, and my servantJob shall pray for you; for, our of regard for him,I will not put you to confusion for your failure tospeak the truth about me, as my servant Job has{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 9}done." So Eliphaz the Temanite, Bildad theShuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite went and didas Jehovah told them, and Jehovah had regard untoJob.
\par}

{\pard\sb360\sa360\fs36 The Restoration of Job

\par}

{\pard
\par}
{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 10}So when Job prayed for his friends, Jehovahchanged his fortunes, giving him double of all he{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 11}had before. Then his brothers and sister and oldfriends came \uc1\u8211* every one of them \uc1\u8211* and dinedwith him at his home; and they condoled withhim, and comforted him for all the misery thatJehovah had brought upon him. Besides, each ofthem made him a present of a piece of money and agold ring.{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 12}Thus in the end Jehovah made Job more blessedthan he was at the first \uc1\u8211* with his fourteen thousandsheep, six thousand camels, one thousand yoke of{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 13}oxen, and one thousand she-asses. Besides, he hadseven sons, and three daughters whom he named{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 14}in the order of their birth Jemimah, Keziah, and{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 15}Keren-happuch. In all the world were no womenfound so fair as the daughters of Job, and theirfather made them sharers in his inheritance withtheir brothers.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 16}After this Job lived a hundred and forty years.Thus he was spared to see not only his children, buthis grandchildren \uc1\u8211* four generations.
\par}

{\pard\sl280\slmult1\fs24\fi360 
{\super\f1\cf2\fs24 17}Then Job died \uc1\u8211* old and full of days.
\par}

